## Features

### 1. Automatic Terminal Pairing

When a `.claude` file is opened and auto-terminal is enabled, the extension:
- Creates a split terminal to the right of the editor
- Sets `CLAUDE_FILE=<filename>` as an env var on the terminal
- Sets the terminal name and icon (Claude icon)
- Auto-starts Claude Code (resuming existing session or creating a new one with `/rename`)

**Session lookup logic** (`findExistingSession()` in `terminal.ts`):
- Encodes the cwd via `dirToProjectName()` (replaces `/` and spaces with `-`)
- Scans `~/.claude/projects/<encoded-cwd>/*.jsonl` for files containing `Session renamed to: \"<name>\"`
- Returns the most recently modified match
- If no match: pipes `/rename "<name>"` into a fresh `claude` process

### 2. Editor ↔ Terminal Sync

- Switching to a `.claude` tab reveals its paired terminal
- Clicking a managed terminal reveals its paired `.claude` editor
- A depth-counted `withSyncGuard()` prevents infinite focus-swap loops and handles nested/overlapping calls

### 3. Session Forking

Fork any session to run parallel agents on the same context:
- Creates a new `.claude` file with `name~N` naming convention (e.g., `hugh~2.claude`)
- Uses `claude --resume "<parent-session-id>" --fork-session` with piped `/rename`
- Each fork gets its own terminal, preserving the 1:1 file↔terminal model
- Dashboard shows forks indented under their parent with a ⑂ glyph
- Fork button (⌇) on each card, also available via command palette

**Utilities** in `utils.ts`: `parseForkName()`, `getForkBase()`, `nextForkName()`

### 4. Dashboard (Cmd+D)

A WebView panel (with CSP) showing all open `.claude` files as cards.

**Each card displays:**
- File name (bold header)
- Status indicator (colored pill): Active / Pending Permission / Waiting on User
- Time since last session activity (e.g. "5m ago")
- Last N messages from the session log (markdown-rendered)
- Running subagents (pulsing green dots with description and type)
- Fork (⌇), Delete (🗑, forks only), and Close (✕) buttons

**Per-directory features:**
- Cards grouped by parent directory with color-coded accent borders
- **+ button** on each directory header to create new `.claude` files (with input validation)

**Scroll anchoring:** Uses `postMessage`-based incremental content updates. Before swapping innerHTML, finds the first visible card as an anchor; after swap, scrolls to keep that card at the same viewport position.

**Auto-refresh triggers:**
- Global `fs.watch` on `~/.claude/hooks/state/` — fires within 500ms of any hook state change
- 10-second interval timer as fallback
- Panel visibility change (full re-render when dashboard becomes visible)

**Security:**
- Content Security Policy blocks external resource loading
- Path validation (`isPathSafe()`) on all webview messages
- Input validation for file creation (reserved names, traversal, special characters)
- Event listener disposables properly tracked and cleaned up

### 5. Subagent Tracking

The dashboard tracks running Agent tool_use calls per session:
- Parses session JSONL logs for `tool_use` blocks with `name: "Agent"`
- **Foreground agents**: Running if no matching `tool_result` exists yet
- **Background agents** (`run_in_background: true`): Extracts `agentId` from the "Async agent launched" confirmation, then checks `<session>/subagents/agent-<agentId>.jsonl` mtime — running if modified within 30s
- Only running agents are displayed (done agents hidden)
- Results cached by logPath with mtime+size validation to avoid re-reading large files

### 6. Close All Non-Claude Files

Command that closes every tab that isn't a `.claude` file or the dashboard. Also disposes unmanaged terminals. Runs automatically on extension activation if `autoSetupOnStart` is enabled.

### 7. Custom Editor Labels

On activation, sets `workbench.editor.customLabels.patterns` so `.claude` files display as just `filename` without the extension.

### 8. Close Confirmation

Closing a `.claude` file that has a paired terminal triggers a confirmation dialog, since it will also kill the terminal (and thus the Claude session). Configurable via settings.

### 9. In-Editor Notifications

When a hook state file is created (agent needs attention), the extension shows a VS Code warning notification with action buttons. The global state watcher runs independently of the dashboard, so notifications appear even when the dashboard is closed. Duplicate notifications are suppressed by tracking timestamps per agent.

